# Home SOC Lab with Wazuh SIEM

## Overview

As part of my independent cybersecurity learning, I built a home Security Operations Center (SOC) lab using Wazuh SIEM.

The purpose of this lab was to gain hands-on experience with log collection, correlation, and endpoint monitoring in a controlled environment using virtual machines.

The lab environment was designed to simulate real-world SOC monitoring scenarios, including authentication events, endpoint activity, and security alert generation.

---

## Objectives

* Deploy a functional SIEM environment for security monitoring practice.
* Centralize logs from Windows and Linux virtual machines.
* Understand authentication, system, and security event logs.
* Simulate real-world attack and user activity scenarios.
* Gain practical experience in SOC-style investigations.

---

## Lab Environment

* Virtual Machines (Windows & Linux)
* Wazuh SIEM Server
* Windows Event Logging
* Linux system logs (syslog)
* Networked lab environment (isolated)

---

## Implementation Details

### SIEM Deployment

I deployed Wazuh in a virtualized environment and configured it as the central log analysis platform for the lab.

Endpoints were connected to the SIEM agent to enable:

* Real-time log forwarding
* Security event monitoring
* Host-based activity tracking

---

### Log Integration

I integrated multiple log sources into the SIEM, including:

* Windows Security Event Logs
* Authentication logs (successful and failed logins)
* System and process activity logs
* Linux system logs via syslog

---

### Security Testing & Simulation

To better understand how SIEM detection works, I simulated common user and security events, including:

* Failed login attempts using incorrect credentials
* Successful authentication events
* User activity on endpoints
* Basic system interaction and log generation

These simulations helped me understand how SIEM tools detect patterns and generate alerts based on log data.

